---
import PageLayout from "@/layouts/Base";
import { Icon } from "astro-icon";

const meta = {
	title: "Match Tile: Mini",
	description: "A compact tile-matching puzzle game for iOS, built with SwiftUI and SpriteKit.",
};
---

<PageLayout meta={meta}>
	<div class="max-w-2xl">
		<div class="mb-8 flex items-center gap-4">
			<img src="/miniMatchIcon.png" alt="Match Tile: Mini app icon" class="h-20 w-20 rounded-2xl" />
			<div>
				<h1 class="title mb-1 text-3xl">Match Tile: Mini</h1>
				<p class="text-gray-500">2023-present</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<section class="mb-8">
			<p class="mb-4">
				A tiny tile-matching puzzle game for iOS. I kept the idea deliberately small: a bright icon,
				a compact board, a level map, lives, coins, boosters, and enough state management to make
				the simple thing behave like a real mobile game.
			</p>
			<p>
				It was one of those projects where the game loop looks simple, then the invisible parts
				start showing up. Persistence. Progression. Economy. All the little systems that make a toy
				feel finished.
			</p>
		</section>

		<div class="mb-12 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
			<a
				href="https://apps.apple.com/es/app/match-tile-mini-puzzle-game/id6473903061?l=en-GB"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noopener noreferrer"
				class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-md bg-accent px-4 py-2 text-bgColor transition-all hover:opacity-80"
			>
				<Icon name="fa-brands:apple" class="h-5 w-5" />
				 App Store
			</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</PageLayout>
